					<div class="context-title">
						<h2>Defining the Problem</h2>
						<div class="line"></div>
					</div>
					<div class="context-info">
						<p class="first-graf">Before any design, it was important to understand what we were designing for; what problems were we trying to solve.</p>
						<p>To gather information, I led <em>working sessions</em> with our client, conducted <em>user research</em>, and began asking important questions:</p><span class="quote">Who are our users? What do they need from a video player? When do they watch online?  Why do they stop?</span>
						<p class="last-graf">These efforts helped define our feature <em>requirements</em> and the key <em>user scenarios</em> we wanted to focus on. As an extra step, I <em>led prioritization sessions</em> with our client to get everyone aligned around our goals.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="outputs">
				<div class="content-grid">
					<div class="outputs-gallery">
						 <a href="images/wave-brainstorm.JPG" rel="gallery-research" class="gallery ">
							<img src="images/wave-brainstorm.JPG" class="border">
						</a>
						<a href="images/wave-research.png" rel="gallery-research" class="gallery two">
							<img src="images/wave-research.png" class="border">
						</a>
					</div>
					<span class="caption">
						<em>Gathering Requirements and Initial User Assumptions</em></br>
						Initial design requirements came out of collaborative working sessions with our team and our stakeholders. Odeally I would conduct user interviews to inform initial requirements. However, given limited time and budget, we could not afford the luxury of upfront, extensive research. In lieu of proper user research, I looked for relevant research and articles online and kept track of my assumptions&mdash;user assumptions helped frame user testing later in the project.
					</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

